revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}
'''The Association for the Protection of Sea-Birds''' was formed in the late 1860s<ref>[http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F82264 National Archives]</ref> by [[Reverend|The Rev.]] [[Henry Frederick Barnes-Lawrence]] the [[Incumbent (ecclesiastical)]] at [[Bridlington Priory]].<ref>''The Saviour of "those fair birds of God"'' Wilson, M p5 [[Bridlington]], [[Bridlington Priory]], 2005</ref> to stop the practice of shooting sea birds for sport, a practice which was legislated for in 1869.<ref>*[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1869/may/04/sea-birds-preservation-bill Hansard: Sea Birds Preservation Bill, Lord's Committee]</ref>
As well as promoting the society in [[Yorkshire]] Barnes-Frederick also set up a branch in [[Ryde]] where he had been a [[Curate]].<ref>'RYDE, SATURDAY, 29 May 1880' [[Isle of Wight Observer]] (Ryde, England), Saturday, 29 May 1880; pg. 4; Issue 1425</ref>

